T1  - PRICE COMPARISON WEBSITES
AU  - Ronayne, David
Y1  - 2021/08/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12504
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1081
EP  - 1110
VL  - 62
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12504
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract The large and growing industry of price comparison websites (PCWs) or ?web aggregators? is poised to benefit consumers by increasing competitive pricing pressure on firms by acquainting shoppers with more prices. However, these sites also charge firms for sales, which feeds back to raise prices. I find that introducing any number of PCWs to a market increases prices for all consumers, both those who use the sites and those who do not. I then use my framework to identify ways in which a more competitive environment could be achieved.
ER  - 

